# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: code-quality
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] In computer programming and software design, **code refactoring** is the process of restructuring existing source code—changing the *factoring*—without changing its external behavior.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Refactoring is intended to improve the design, structure, or implementation of the software (its *non-functional* attributes), while preserving its functionality.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Potential advantages of refactoring may include improved code readability and reduced complexity; these can improve the source code's maintainability and create a simpler, cleaner, or more expressive internal architecture or object model to improve extensibility.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Another potential goal for refactoring is improved performance; software engineers face an ongoing challenge to write programs that perform faster or use less memory.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Despite the availability of metrics intended to assess such attributes, developers often do not rely on them when making refactoring decisions due to concerns about its practical usefulness.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Typically, refactoring applies a series of standardized basic *micro-refactorings*, each of which is (usually) a tiny change in a computer program's source code that either preserves the behavior of the software, or at least does not modify its conformance to functional requirements.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Many development environments provide automated support for performing the mechanical aspects of these basic refactorings.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] If done well, code refactoring may help software developers discover and fix hidden or dormant bugs or vulnerabilities in the system by simplifying the underlying logic and eliminating unnecessary levels of complexity.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] If done poorly, it may fail the requirement that external functionality not be changed, and may thus introduce new bugs.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Refactoring is usually motivated by noticing a code smell.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] For example, the method at hand may be very long, or it may be a near duplicate of another nearby method.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Once recognized, such problems can be addressed by *refactoring* the source code, or transforming it into a new form that behaves the same as before but that no longer "smells".
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] For a long routine, one or more smaller subroutines can be extracted.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] For duplicate routines, the duplication can be removed and replaced with one shared function.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Failure to perform refactoring can result in accumulating technical debt; on the other hand, refactoring is one of the primary means of repaying technical debt.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] There are two general categories of benefits to the activity of refactoring.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] It is easier to extend the capabilities of the application if it uses recognizable design patterns, and it provides some flexibility where none before may have existed.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Performance engineering can remove inefficiencies in programs, known as software bloat, arising from traditional software-development strategies that aim to minimize an application's development time rather than the time it takes to run.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Performance engineering can also tailor software to the hardware on which it runs, for example, to take advantage of parallel processors and vector units.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] There are two possible times for refactoring.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Corrective refactoring – a subsequent developer performs refactoring to correct code smells as they occur.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] A method that balances preventive and corrective refactoring is "shared responsibility for refactoring".
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] This approach splits the refactoring action into two stages and two roles.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] The original developer of the code just prepares the code for refactoring, and when the code smells form, a subsequent developer carries out the actual refactoring action.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Refactoring requires extracting the software system structure, data models, and intra-application dependencies to get back knowledge of an existing software system.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] The turnover of teams implies missing or inaccurate knowledge of the current state of a system and about design decisions made by departing developers.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Further code refactoring activities may require additional effort to regain this knowledge.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Refactoring activities generate architectural modifications that deteriorate the structural architecture of a software system.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Such deterioration affects architectural properties such as maintainability and comprehensibility, which can lead to a complete re-development of software systems.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Automatic unit tests should be set up before refactoring to ensure routines still behave as expected.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Unit tests can bring stability to even large refactors when performed with a single atomic commit.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] A common strategy to allow safe and atomic refactors spanning multiple projects is to store all projects in a single repository, known as monorepo.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] With unit testing in place, refactoring is then an iterative cycle of making a small program transformation, testing it to ensure correctness, and making another small transformation.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] If at any point a test fails, the last small change is undone and repeated in a different way.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Through many small steps the program moves from where it was to where you want it to be.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] For this very iterative process to be practical, the tests must run very quickly, or the programmer would have to spend a large fraction of their time waiting for the tests to finish.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Proponents of extreme programming and other agile software development describe this activity as an integral part of the software development cycle.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Refactoring applies to test code as well as production code; empirical studies show that test refactoring primarily targets low-quality test code exhibiting test smells, and improves test code coupling, cohesion, and size, though it does not necessarily improve code coverage.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Here are some examples of micro-refactorings; some of these may only apply to certain languages or language types.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] A longer list can be found in Martin Fowler's refactoring book and website.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Many development environments provide automated support for these micro-refactorings.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] For instance, a programmer could click on the name of a variable and then select the "Encapsulate field" refactoring from a context menu.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] The IDE would then prompt for additional details, typically with sensible defaults and a preview of the code changes.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] After confirmation by the programmer, it would carry out the required changes throughout the code.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Static program analysis (called "linting" when performed on less strict interpreted languages) detects problems in a valid but substandard program.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Transformations modify the syntactic representation of a program.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Some modifications alter the semantics or structure of the program in a way that improves its flexibility or robustness.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Such modifications require knowledge of the problem domain and intended logic, and thus are infeasible to automate.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Modifications exist that make the program easier to read and modify, but which do not alter the underlying logic of the program; these transformations can be automated.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] While the term *refactoring* originally referred exclusively to refactoring of software code, in recent years code written in hardware description languages has also been refactored.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] The term *hardware refactoring* is used as a shorthand term for refactoring of code in hardware description languages.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Since hardware description languages are not considered to be programming languages by most hardware engineers, hardware refactoring is to be considered a separate field from traditional code refactoring.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Automated refactoring of analog hardware descriptions (in VHDL-AMS) has been proposed by Zeng and Huss.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] In their approach, refactoring preserves the simulated behavior of a hardware design.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] The non-functional measurement that improves is that refactored code can be processed by standard synthesis tools, while the original code cannot.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Refactoring of digital hardware description languages, albeit manual refactoring, has also been investigated by Synopsys fellow Mike Keating.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] His target is to make complex systems easier to understand, which increases the designers' productivity.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] The first known use of the term "refactoring" in the published literature was in a September 1990 article by William Opdyke and Ralph Johnson.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] All of these resources provide a catalog of common methods for refactoring; a refactoring method has a description of how to apply the method and indicators for when you should (or should not) apply the method.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Martin Fowler's book *Refactoring: Improving the Design of Existing Code* is the canonical reference.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] The terms "factoring" and "factoring out" have been used in this way in the Forth community since at least the early 1980s.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Chapter Six of Leo Brodie's book *Thinking Forth* (1984) is dedicated to the subject.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] In extreme programming, the Extract Method refactoring technique has essentially the same meaning as factoring in Forth: to break down a "word" (or function) into smaller, more easily maintained functions.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Refactorings can also be reconstructed posthoc to produce concise descriptions of complex software changes recorded in software repositories like Git.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Many software development tools have features for refactoring.
[src:code-quality/code-refactoring] Most dialects include powerful refactoring tools.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] In computer programming, a **code smell** is any characteristic of source code that hints at a deeper problem.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] Determining what a code smell is and is not is subjective, and varies by language, developer, and development methodology.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] The term was popularized by Kent Beck on WardsWiki in the late 1990s.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] Usage of the term increased after it was featured in the 1999 book *Refactoring: Improving the Design of Existing Code* by Martin Fowler.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] It is also a term used by agile programmers.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] One way to look at smells is with respect to principles and quality: "Smells are certain structures in the code that indicate violation of fundamental design principles and negatively impact design quality".
[src:code-quality/code-smell] Code smells are usually not bugs; they are not technically incorrect and do not prevent the program from functioning.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] Instead, they indicate weaknesses in design that may slow down development or increase the risk of bugs or failures in the future.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] Bad code smells can be an indicator of factors that contribute to technical debt.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] Martin calls a list of code smells a "value system" for software craftsmanship.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] Contrary to these severe interpretations, Cunningham's original definition was that a smell is a suggestion that something may be wrong, not evidence that there is already a problem.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] From the point of view of a programmer charged with performing refactoring, code smells are heuristics to indicate when to refactor, and what specific refactoring techniques to use.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] Thus, a code smell is a driver for refactoring.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] Tools such as Checkstyle, PMD, FindBugs, and SonarQube can automatically identify code smells.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] identical or very similar code that exists in more than one location.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] a single change that needs to be applied to multiple classes at the same time.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] that contains too many types or contains many unrelated methods.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] these should be coded as named constants, to improve readability and to avoid programming errors.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] can and should be externalized into resource files/scripts, or other data stores such as databases where possible, to facilitate localization of software if it is intended to be deployed in different regions.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] a type cast which breaks the abstraction model; the abstraction may have to be refactored or eliminated.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] Occurs when a group of variables are passed around together in various parts of the program.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] In general, this suggests that it would be more appropriate to formally group the different variables together into a single object, and pass around only the new object instead.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] a long list of parameters is hard to read, and makes calling and testing the function complicated.
[src:code-quality/code-smell] It may indicate that the purpose of the function is ill-conceived and that the code should be refactored so responsibility is assigned in a more clean-cut way.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] In computer programming, **cohesion** refers to the *degree to which the elements inside a module belong together*.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] In one sense, it is a measure of the strength of relationship between the methods and data of a class and some unifying purpose or concept served by that class.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] In another sense, it is a measure of the strength of relationship between the class's methods and data.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] Cohesion is an ordinal type of measurement and is usually described as “high cohesion” or “low cohesion”.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] Modules with high cohesion tend to be preferable, because high cohesion is associated with several desirable software traits including robustness, reliability, reusability, and understandability.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] In contrast, low cohesion is associated with undesirable traits such as being difficult to maintain, test, reuse, or understand.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] Cohesion is often contrasted with coupling.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] High cohesion often correlates with loose coupling, and vice versa.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] The software metrics of coupling and cohesion were invented by Larry Constantine in the late 1960s as part of Structured Design, based on characteristics of “good” programming practices that reduced maintenance and modification costs.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] Structured Design, cohesion and coupling were published in the article *Stevens, Myers & Constantine* (1974) and the book *Yourdon & Constantine* (1979).
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] The latter two subsequently became standard terms in software engineering.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] In object-oriented programming, a class is said to have high cohesion if the methods that serve the class are similar in many aspects.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] In a highly cohesive system, code readability and reusability is increased, while complexity is kept manageable.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] While in principle a module can have perfect cohesion by only consisting of a single, atomic element – having a single function, for example – in practice complex tasks are not expressible by a single, simple element.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] Thus a single-element module has an element that is either too complicated to accomplish a task, or too narrow and thus tightly coupled to other modules.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] Thus cohesion is balanced with both unit complexity and coupling.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] Cohesion is a qualitative measure, meaning that the source code is examined using a rubric to determine a classification.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] Coincidental cohesion is when parts of a module are grouped arbitrarily.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] The only relationship between the parts is that they have been grouped together (e.g., a “Utilities” class).
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] Temporal cohesion is when parts of a module are grouped according to the time in which they are processed.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] The parts are processed at a particular time in program execution (e.g., a function that is called after catching an exception that closes open files, creates an error log, and notifies the user).
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] Procedural cohesion is when parts of a module are grouped because they always follow a certain sequence of execution (e.g., a function that checks file permissions and then opens the file).
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] Communicational cohesion is when parts of a module are grouped because they operate on the same data (e.g., a module that operates on the same record of information).
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] Sequential cohesion is when parts of a module are grouped because the output from one part is the input to another part like an assembly line (e.g., a function that reads data from a file and processes the data).
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] Although cohesion is a ranking type of scale, the ranks do not indicate a steady progression of improved cohesion.
[src:code-quality/cohesion-computer-science] Studies by Larry Constantine, Edward Yourdon, and Steve McConnell indicate that the first two types of cohesion are inferior, communicational and sequential cohesion are very good, and functional cohesion is superior.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] In software engineering, **coupling** is the degree of interdependence between software modules, a measure of how closely connected two routines or modules are, and the strength of the relationships between modules.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling is not binary but multi-dimensional.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling is usually contrasted with cohesion.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Low coupling often correlates with high cohesion, and vice versa.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Low coupling is often thought to be a sign of a well-structured computer system and a good design, and when combined with high cohesion, supports the general goals of high readability and maintainability.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] The software quality metrics of coupling and cohesion were invented by Larry Constantine in the late 1960s as part of a structured design, based on characteristics of “good” programming practices that reduced maintenance and modification costs.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Structured design, including cohesion and coupling, were published in the article *Stevens, Myers & Constantine* (1974) and the book *Yourdon & Constantine* (1979), and the latter subsequently became standard terms.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling and cohesion are terms which occur together very frequently.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling refers to the interdependencies between modules, while cohesion describes how related the functions within a single module are.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Low cohesion implies that a given module performs tasks which are not very related to each other and hence can create problems as the module becomes large.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling can be "low" (also "loose" and "weak") or "high" (also "tight" and "strong").
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] A module here refers to a subroutine of any kind, i.e. a set of one or more statements having a name and preferably its own set of variable names.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Content coupling is said to occur when one module uses the code of another module, for instance a branch.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Common coupling is said to occur when several modules have access to the same global data.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] But it can lead to uncontrolled error propagation and unforeseen side-effects when changes are made.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] This is basically related to the communication to external tools and devices.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Control coupling is one module controlling the flow of another, by passing it information on what to do (e.g., passing a what-to-do flag).
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] and use only parts of it, possibly different parts (e.g., passing a whole record to a function that needs only one field of it).
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] In this situation, a modification in a field that a module does not need may lead to changing the way the module reads the record.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] , even if they do not utilize the modified attribute.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Data coupling occurs when modules share data through, for example, parameters.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Each datum is an elementary piece, and these are the only data shared (e.g., passing an integer to a function that computes a square root).
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Describes the relationship between a child and its parent.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] The child is connected to its parent, but the parent is not connected to the child.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] It is when two actions are bundled together into one module just because they happen to occur at the same time.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] In recent work various other coupling concepts have been investigated and used as indicators for different modularization principles used in practice.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] The goal of defining and measuring this type of coupling is to provide a run-time evaluation of a software system.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] It has been argued that static coupling metrics lose precision when dealing with an intensive use of dynamic binding or inheritance.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] In the attempt to solve this issue, dynamic coupling measures have been taken into account.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] This kind of a coupling metric considers the conceptual similarities between software entities using, for example, comments and identifiers and relying on techniques such as latent semantic indexing (LSI).
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Assembly of modules might require more effort and/or time due to the increased inter-module dependency.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] A particular module might be harder to reuse and/or test because dependent modules must be included.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Longer messages require more CPU and memory to produce.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] To optimize runtime performance, message length must be minimized and message meaning must be maximized.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Since a message must be transmitted in full to retain its complete meaning, message transmission must be optimized.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Longer messages require more CPU and memory to transmit and receive.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Also, when necessary, receivers must reassemble a message into its original state to completely receive it.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Hence, to optimize runtime performance, message length must be minimized and message meaning must be maximized.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Message protocols and messages themselves often contain extra information (i.e., packet, structure, definition and language information).
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Hence, the receiver often needs to translate a message into a more refined form by removing extra characters and structure information and/or by converting values from one type to another.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Any sort of translation increases CPU and/or memory overhead.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] To optimize runtime performance, message form and content must be reduced and refined to maximize its meaning and reduce translation.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] All messages must be interpreted by the receiver.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Simple messages such as integers might not require additional processing to be interpreted.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] messages require a parser and a string transformer for them to exhibit intended meanings.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] To optimize runtime performance, messages must be refined and reduced to minimize interpretation overhead.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] One approach to decreasing coupling is functional design, which seeks to limit the responsibilities of modules along functionality.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Low coupling refers to a relationship in which one module interacts with another module through a simple and stable interface and does not need to be concerned with the other module's internal implementation (see Information Hiding).
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Systems such as CORBA or COM allow objects to communicate with each other without having to know anything about the other object's implementation.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Both of these systems even allow for objects to communicate with objects written in other languages.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling describes the degree and nature of dependency between software components, focusing on what they share (e.g., data, control flow, technology) and how tightly they are bound.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] It evaluates two key dimensions: strength, which measures how difficult it is to change the dependency, and scope (or visibility), which indicates how widely the dependency is exposed across modules or boundaries.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Traditional coupling types typically include content coupling, common coupling, control coupling, stamp coupling, external coupling, and data coupling.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Connascence, introduced by Meilir Page-Jones, provides a systematic framework for analyzing and measuring coupling dependencies.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Connascence can be categorized into static (detectable at compile-time) and dynamic (detectable at runtime) forms.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Static connascence refers to compile-time dependencies, such as method signatures, while dynamic connascence refers to runtime dependencies, which can manifest in forms like connascence of timing, values, or algorithm.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Each coupling flavor can exhibit multiple types of connascence, a specific type, or, in rare cases, none at all, depending on how the dependency is implemented.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Common types of connascence include connascence of name, type, position, and meaning.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Certain coupling types naturally align with specific connascence types; for example, data coupling often involves connascence of name or type.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] However, not every combination of coupling and connascence is practically meaningful.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Dependencies relying on parameter order in a method signature demonstrate connascence of position, which is fragile and difficult to refactor because reordering parameters breaks the interface.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] In contrast, connascence of name, which relies on field or parameter names, is generally more resilient to change.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Connascence types themselves exhibit a natural hierarchy of strength, with connascence of name typically considered weaker than connascence of meaning.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Dependencies spanning module boundaries or distributed systems typically have higher coordination costs, increasing the difficulty of refactoring and propagating changes across distant boundaries.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Modern practices, such as dependency injection and interface-based programming, are often employed to reduce coupling strength and improve the maintainability of dependencies.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] While coupling identifies what is shared between components, connascence evaluates how those dependencies behave, how changes propagate, and how difficult they are to refactor.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Strength, locality, and degree are interrelated; dependencies with high strength, wide scope, and spanning distant boundaries are significantly harder to refactor and maintain.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Together, coupling provides a high-level overview of dependency relationships, while connascence offers a granular framework for analyzing dependency strength, locality, degree, and resilience to change, supporting the design of maintainable and robust systems.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling in Software Engineering describes a version of metrics associated with this concept.
[src:code-quality/coupling-computer-programming] `Coupling(C)` makes the value larger the more coupled the module is.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Cyclomatic complexity is computed using the control-flow graph of the program.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] The nodes of the graph correspond to indivisible groups of commands of a program, and a directed edge connects two nodes if the second command might be executed immediately after the first command.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Cyclomatic complexity may also be applied to individual functions, modules, methods, or classes within a program.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] One testing strategy, called basis path testing by McCabe who first proposed it, is to test each linearly independent path through the program.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] In this case, the number of test cases will equal the cyclomatic complexity of the program.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] There are multiple ways to define cyclomatic complexity of a section of source code.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] One common way is the number of linearly independent paths within it.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] A set S of paths is linearly independent if the edge set of any path P in S is not the union of edge sets of the paths in some subset of $S/P$ .
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] If the source code contained no control flow statements (conditionals or decision points) the complexity would be 1, since there would be only a single path through the code.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] If the code had one single-condition IF statement, there would be two paths through the code: one where the IF statement is TRUE and another one where it is FALSE.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Two nested single-condition IFs, or one IF with two conditions, would produce a complexity of 3.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Another way to define the cyclomatic complexity of a program is to look at its control-flow graph, a directed graph containing the basic blocks of the program, with an edge between two basic blocks if control may pass from the first to the second.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] An alternative formulation of this, as originally proposed, is to use a graph in which each exit point is connected back to the entry point.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] In this case, the graph is strongly connected.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] This may be seen as calculating the number of linearly independent cycles that exist in the graph: those cycles that do not contain other cycles within themselves.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Because each exit point loops back to the entry point, there is at least one such cycle for each exit point.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Cyclomatic complexity may be applied to several such programs or subprograms at the same time (to all of the methods in a class, for example).
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] In these cases, P will equal the number of programs in question, and each subprogram will appear as a disconnected subset of the graph.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] McCabe showed that the cyclomatic complexity of a structured program with only one entry point and one exit point is equal to the number of decision points ("if" statements or conditional loops) contained in that program plus one.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] This is true only for decision points counted at the lowest, machine-level instructions.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Decisions involving compound predicates like those found in high-level languages like `IF cond1 AND cond2 THEN ...` should be counted in terms of predicate variables involved.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] In this example, one should count two decision points because at machine level it is equivalent to `IF cond1 THEN IF cond2 THEN ...`.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Cyclomatic complexity may be extended to a program with multiple exit points.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] In this case, it is equal to $\pi -s+2,$ where $\pi$ is the number of decision points in the program and s is the number of exit points.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] An even subgraph of a graph (also known as an Eulerian subgraph) is one in which every vertex is incident with an even number of edges.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Such subgraphs are unions of cycles and isolated vertices.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Subgraphs will be identified with their edge sets, which is equivalent to only considering those even subgraphs which contain all vertices of the full graph.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] The set of all even subgraphs of a graph is closed under symmetric difference, and may thus be viewed as a vector space over GF(2).
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] This vector space is called the cycle space of the graph.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] The cyclomatic number of the graph is defined as the dimension of this space.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Since GF(2) has two elements and the cycle space is necessarily finite, the cyclomatic number is also equal to the 2-logarithm of the number of elements in the cycle space.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] A basis for the cycle space is easily constructed by first fixing a spanning forest of the graph, and then considering the cycles formed by one edge not in the forest and the path in the forest connecting the endpoints of that edge.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] These cycles form a basis for the cycle space.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] The cyclomatic number also equals the number of edges not in a maximal spanning forest of a graph.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Since the number of edges in a maximal spanning forest of a graph is equal to the number of vertices minus the number of components, the formula $E-N+P$ defines the cyclomatic number.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] which is read as "the rank of the first homology group of the graph *G* relative to the terminal nodes *t*".
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] This cyclomatic complexity can be calculated.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] It may also be computed via absolute Betti number by identifying the terminal nodes on a given component, or drawing paths connecting the exits to the entrance.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] If a (connected) control-flow graph is considered a one-dimensional CW complex called X , the fundamental group of X will be $\pi _{1}(X)\cong \mathbb {Z} ^{*n}$ .
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] The value of $n+1$ is the cyclomatic complexity.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] The fundamental group counts how many loops there are through the graph up to homotopy, aligning as expected.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] One of McCabe's original applications was to limit the complexity of routines during program development.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] He recommended that programmers should count the complexity of the modules they are developing, and split them into smaller modules whenever the cyclomatic complexity of the module exceeded 10.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] This practice was adopted by the NIST Structured Testing methodology, which observed that since McCabe's original publication, the figure of 10 had received substantial corroborating evidence.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] However, it also noted that in some circumstances it may be appropriate to relax the restriction and permit modules with a complexity as high as 15.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Section VI of McCabe's 1976 paper is concerned with determining what the control-flow graphs (CFGs) of non-structured programs look like in terms of their subgraphs, which McCabe identified.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] (For details, see structured program theorem.) McCabe concluded that section by proposing a numerical measure of how close to the structured programming ideal a given program is, i.e. its "structuredness".
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] McCabe called the measure he devised for this purpose essential complexity.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] To calculate this measure, the original CFG is iteratively reduced by identifying subgraphs that have a single-entry and a single-exit point, which are then replaced by a single node.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] This reduction corresponds to what a human would do if they extracted a subroutine from the larger piece of code.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] (Nowadays such a process would fall under the umbrella term of refactoring.) McCabe's reduction method was later called *condensation* in some textbooks, because it was seen as a generalization of the condensation to components used in graph theory.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] If a program is structured, then McCabe's reduction/condensation process reduces it to a single CFG node.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] In contrast, if the program is not structured, the iterative process will identify the irreducible part.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] The essential complexity measure defined by McCabe is simply the cyclomatic complexity of this irreducible graph, so it will be precisely 1 for all structured programs, but greater than one for non-structured programs.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Another application of cyclomatic complexity is in determining the number of test cases that are necessary to achieve thorough test coverage of a particular module.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] All three of the above numbers may be equal: branch coverage $\leq$ cyclomatic complexity $\leq$ number of paths.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] For example, consider a program that consists of two sequential if-then-else statements.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] In this example, two test cases are sufficient to achieve a complete branch coverage, while four are necessary for complete path coverage.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] The cyclomatic complexity of the program is 3 (as the strongly connected graph for the program contains 8 edges, 7 nodes, and 1 connected component) (8 − 7 + 2).
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] In general, in order to fully test a module, all execution paths through the module should be exercised.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] This implies a module with a high complexity number requires more testing effort than a module with a lower value since the higher complexity number indicates more pathways through the code.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] This also implies that a module with higher complexity is more difficult to understand since the programmer must understand the different pathways and the results of those pathways.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Cyclomatic complexity captures only one aspect of software, so relying on it alone may provide an incomplete representation of the overall complexity of a program.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Unfortunately, it is not always practical to test all possible paths through a program.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Considering the example above, each time an additional if-then-else statement is added, the number of possible paths grows by a factor of 2.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] As the program grows in this fashion, it quickly reaches the point where testing all of the paths becomes impractical.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] One common testing strategy, espoused for example by the NIST Structured Testing methodology, is to use the cyclomatic complexity of a module to determine the number of white-box tests that are required to obtain sufficient coverage of the module.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] In almost all cases, according to such a methodology, a module should have at least as many tests as its cyclomatic complexity.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] In most cases, this number of tests is adequate to exercise all the relevant paths of the function.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] As an example of a function that requires more than mere branch coverage to test accurately, reconsider the above function.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] However, assume that to avoid a bug occurring, any code that calls either `f1()` or `f3()` must also call the other.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Assuming that the results of `c1()` and `c2()` are independent, the function as presented above contains a bug.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] If, however, we use cyclomatic complexity to indicate the number of tests we require, the number increases to 3.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Either of these tests will expose the bug.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Multiple studies have investigated the correlation between McCabe's cyclomatic complexity number with the frequency of defects occurring in a function or method.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Some studies find a positive correlation between cyclomatic complexity and defects; functions and methods that have the highest complexity tend to also contain the most defects.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] However, the correlation between cyclomatic complexity and program size (typically measured in lines of code) has been demonstrated many times.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Les Hatton has claimed that complexity has the same predictive ability as lines of code.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Studies that controlled for program size (i.e., comparing modules that have different complexities but similar size) are generally less conclusive, with many finding no significant correlation, while others do find correlation.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Some researchers question the validity of the methods used by the studies finding no correlation.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Although this relation likely exists, it is not easily used in practice.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Since program size is not a controllable feature of commercial software, the usefulness of McCabe's number has been questioned.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] The essence of this observation is that larger programs tend to be more complex and to have more defects.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] Reducing the cyclomatic complexity of code is not proven to reduce the number of errors or bugs in that code.
[src:code-quality/cyclomatic-complexity] International safety standards like ISO 26262, however, mandate coding guidelines that recommend to monitor and aim to reduce code complexity, where complexity is high additional measures including scrutiny of the more difficult verification and validation activities including testing is expected.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] Overly defensive programming, however, may safeguard against errors that will never be encountered, thus incurring run-time and maintenance costs.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] Secure programming is the subset of defensive programming concerned with computer security.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] Security is the concern, not necessarily safety or availability (the software may be allowed to fail in certain ways).
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] The function will result in undefined behavior when the input is over 1000 characters.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] Some programmers may not feel that this is a problem, supposing that no user will enter such a long input.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] This particular bug demonstrates a vulnerability which enables buffer overflow exploits.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] Offensive programming is a category of defensive programming, with the added emphasis that certain errors should *not* be handled defensively.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] In this practice, only errors from outside the program's control are to be handled (such as user input); the software itself, as well as data from within the program's line of defense, are to be trusted in this methodology.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] If existing code is tested and known to work, reusing it may reduce the chance of bugs being introduced.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] However, reusing code is not *always* good practice.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] Reuse of existing code, especially when widely distributed, can allow for exploits to be created that target a wider audience than would otherwise be possible and brings with it all the security and vulnerabilities of the reused code.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] When considering using existing source code, a quick review of the modules(sub-sections such as classes or functions) will help eliminate or make the developer aware of any potential vulnerabilities and ensure it is suitable to use in the project.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] Before reusing old source code, libraries, APIs, configurations and so forth, it must be considered if the old work is valid for reuse, or if it is likely to be prone to legacy problems.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] Legacy problems are problems inherent when old designs are expected to work with today's requirements, especially when the old designs were not developed or tested with those requirements in mind.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] Malicious users are likely to invent new kinds of representations of incorrect data.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] For example, if a program attempts to reject accessing the file "/etc/passwd", a cracker might pass another variant of this file name, like "/etc/./passwd".
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] Canonicalization libraries can be employed to avoid bugs due to non-canonical input.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] Assume that code constructs that appear to be problem prone (similar to known vulnerabilities, etc.) are bugs and potential security flaws.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] The basic rule of thumb is: "I'm not aware of all types of security exploits.
[src:code-quality/defensive-programming] I must protect against those I *do* know of and then I must be proactive!".
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] "**Don't repeat yourself**" (**DRY**) is a principle of software development aimed at reducing repetition of information which is likely to change, replacing it with abstractions that are less likely to change, or using data normalization which avoids redundancy in the first place.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] The DRY principle is stated as "Every piece of knowledge must have a single, unambiguous, authoritative representation within a system".
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] The principle has been formulated by Andy Hunt and Dave Thomas in their book *The Pragmatic Programmer*.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] They apply it quite broadly to include database schemas, test plans, the build system, even documentation.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] When the DRY principle is applied successfully, a modification of any single element of a system does not require a change in other logically unrelated elements.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] Additionally, elements that are logically related all change predictably and uniformly, and are thus kept in sync.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] Besides using methods and subroutines in their code, Thomas and Hunt rely on code generators, automatic build systems, and scripting languages to observe the DRY principle across layers.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] A particular case of DRY is the single choice principle.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] It was defined by Bertrand Meyer as: "Whenever a software system must support a set of alternatives, one and only one module in the system should know their exhaustive list." It was applied when designing Eiffel.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] The opposing view to DRY is called WET, a backronym commonly taken to stand for *write everything twice* (alternatively *write every time*, *we enjoy typing* or *waste everyone's time*).
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] WET solutions are common in multi-tiered architectures where a developer may be tasked with, for example, adding a comment field on a form in a web application.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] The text string "comment" might be repeated in the label, the HTML tag, in a read function name, a private variable, database DDL, queries, and so on.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] A DRY approach eliminates that redundancy by using frameworks that reduce or eliminate all those editing tasks except the most important ones, leaving the extensibility of adding new knowledge variables in one place.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] This conceptualization of "WET" as an alternative to "DRY" programming has been around since at least 2002 in the Java world, though it is not known who coined the term.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] Another approach to abstractions is to *avoid hasty abstractions* (AHA).
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] AHA is rooted in the understanding that the deeper the investment engineers have made into abstracting a piece of software, the more they perceive that the cost of that investment can never be recovered (sunk cost fallacy).
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] Thus, engineers tend to continue to iterate on the same abstraction each time the requirement changes.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] AHA programming assumes that both WET and DRY solutions inevitably create software that is rigid and difficult to maintain.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] Instead of starting with an abstraction, or abstracting at a specific number of duplications, software can be more flexible and robust if abstraction is done when it is needed, or, when the duplication itself has become the barrier and it is known how the abstraction needs to function.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] Dodds, it is optimizing for change first, and avoiding premature optimization.
[src:code-quality/don-t-repeat-yourself] The term was coined by software engineer Cher Scarlett and the practice was described originally by software engineer and author Sandi Metz as "prefer duplication over the wrong abstraction".
[src:code-quality/kiss-principle] The acronym "Keep it simple, stupid" was reportedly coined by Kelly Johnson, lead engineer at the Lockheed Skunk Works (creators of the Lockheed U-2 and SR-71 Blackbird spy planes, among many others).
[src:code-quality/kiss-principle] However, the variant "Keep it Short and Simple" is attested from a 1938 issue of the *Minneapolis Star*.
[src:code-quality/kiss-principle] While popular usage has transcribed it for decades as "Keep it simple, stupid", Johnson transcribed it simply as "Keep it simple stupid" (no comma), and this reading is still used by many authors.
[src:code-quality/kiss-principle] The principle is best exemplified by the story of Johnson handing a team of design engineers a handful of tools, with the challenge that the jet aircraft they were designing must be repairable by an average mechanic in the field under combat conditions with only these tools.
[src:code-quality/kiss-principle] Hence, the "stupid" refers to the relationship between the way things break and the sophistication available to repair them.
[src:code-quality/kiss-principle] The acronym has been used by many in the U.S. military, especially the U.S.
[src:code-quality/kiss-principle] Navy and United States Air Force, and in the field of software development.
[src:code-quality/kiss-principle] Heath Robinson contraptions and Rube Goldberg's machines, intentionally overly-complex solutions to simple tasks or problems, are humorous examples of "non-KISS" solutions.
[src:code-quality/kiss-principle] Master animator Richard Williams explains the KISS principle in his book *The Animator's Survival Kit*, and Disney's Nine Old Men write about it in *Disney Animation: The Illusion of Life*, a considerable work of the genre.
[src:code-quality/kiss-principle] The problem faced is that inexperienced animators may "over-animate" in their works; that is, a character may move too much and do too much.
[src:code-quality/kiss-principle] In the Filipino neo-noir film *Segurista*, KISS is invoked by Mrs Librada (played by Liza Lorena) as an approach to selling insurance.
[src:code-quality/kiss-principle] In the American version of *The Office*, Michael Scott's advice to Dwight Schrute before making any decision is KISS (Keep it Simple, Stupid).
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] In computer programming, a **naming convention** is a set of rules for choosing the character sequence to be used for identifiers which denote variables, types, functions, and other entities in source code and documentation.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] The choice of naming conventions can be a controversial issue, with partisans of each holding theirs to be the best and others to be inferior.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Colloquially, this is said to be a matter of dogma.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Many companies have also established their own set of conventions.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] The exact rules of a naming convention depend on the context in which they are employed.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Nevertheless, there are several common elements that influence most if not all naming conventions in common use today.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Some naming conventions limit whether letters may appear in uppercase or lowercase.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Other conventions do not restrict letter case, but attach a well-defined interpretation based on letter case.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Some naming conventions specify whether alphabetic, numeric, or alphanumeric characters may be used, and if so, in what sequence.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] A common recommendation is "Use meaningful identifiers." A single word may not be as meaningful, or specific, as multiple words.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Consequently, some naming conventions specify rules for the treatment of "compound" identifiers containing more than one word.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] As most programming languages do not allow whitespace in identifiers, a method of delimiting each word is needed to make it easier for subsequent readers to interpret which characters belong to which word.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Historically some early languages, notably FORTRAN (1955) and ALGOL (1958), allowed spaces within identifiers, determining the end of identifiers by context.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] This was abandoned in later languages due to the difficulty of tokenization.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] It is possible to write names by simply concatenating words, and this is sometimes used, as in `mypackage` for Java package names, though legibility suffers for longer terms, so usually some form of separation is used.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] One approach is to delimit separate words with a non-alphanumeric character.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] The two characters commonly used for this purpose are the hyphen ("-") and the underscore ("_"); e.g., the two-word name "`two words`" would be represented as "`two-words`" or "`two_words`".
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] The hyphen is commonly used by when writing COBOL (1959), Forth (1970), and Lisp (1958); it is also common in Unix for commands and packages, and is used in CSS.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] By contrast, languages in the FORTRAN/ALGOL tradition, notably languages in the C and Pascal families, used the hyphen for the subtraction infix operator, and did not wish to require spaces around it (as free-form languages), preventing its use in identifiers.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] An alternative is to use underscores; this is common in the C family (including Python), with lowercase words, being found for example in *The C Programming Language* (1978), and has come to be known as snake case or *snail case*.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Underscores with uppercase, as in UPPER_CASE, are commonly used for C preprocessor macros, hence known as MACRO_CASE, and for environment variables in Unix, such as BASH_VERSION in bash.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Sometimes this is humorously referred to as SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE (alternatively SCREAMING_SNAIL_CASE).
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Another approach is to indicate word boundaries using medial capitalization, called "camelCase", "PascalCase", and many other names, thus respectively rendering "`two words`" as "`twoWords`" or "`TwoWords`".
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] This convention is commonly used in Pascal, Java, C#, and Visual Basic.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Treatment of initialisms in identifiers (e.g. the "XML" and "HTTP" in `XMLHttpRequest`) varies.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Some dictate that they be lowercase (e.g.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] `XmlHttpRequest`) to ease typing, readability and ease of segmentation, whereas others leave them uppercased (e.g.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Perhaps the most well-known is Hungarian notation, which encodes either the purpose ("Apps Hungarian") or the type ("Systems Hungarian") of a variable in its name.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] For example, the prefix "sz" for the variable szName indicates that the variable is a null-terminated string.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] A style used for very short (eight characters and less) could be: LCCIIL01, where LC would be the application (Letters of Credit), C for COBOL, IIL for the particular process subset, and the 01 a sequence number.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] This sort of convention is still in active use in mainframes dependent upon JCL and is also seen in the 8.3 (maximum eight characters with period separator followed by three character file type) MS-DOS style.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] IBM's "OF Language" was documented in an IMS (Information Management System) manual.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] It detailed the PRIME-MODIFIER-CLASS word scheme, which consisted of names like "CUST-ACT-NO" to indicate "customer account number".
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] PRIME words were meant to indicate major "entities" of interest to a system.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] MODIFIER words were used for additional refinement, qualification and readability.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] CLASS words ideally would be a very short list of data types relevant to a particular application.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Common CLASS words might be: NO (number), ID (identifier), TXT (text), AMT (amount), QTY (quantity), FL (flag), CD (code), W (work) and so forth.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] In practice, the available CLASS words would be a list of less than two dozen terms.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] CLASS words, typically positioned on the right (suffix), served much the same purpose as Hungarian notation prefixes.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] The purpose of CLASS words, in addition to consistency, was to specify to the programmer the data type of a particular data field.
[src:code-quality/naming-convention-programming] Prior to the acceptance of BOOLEAN (two values only) fields, FL (flag) would indicate a field with only two possible values.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Modularity is a specific application of concerns to system components (separation by size).
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] In modular systems, each module encapsulates a single concern, and modules are designed, implemented, and understood in isolation before being composed into a larger system.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] While modularity is the most common and recognizable embodiment of SoC in code structure, the principle of Separation of concerns is broader.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] For example, separating requirements analysis from implementation in a project timeline, or separating functional from non-functional requirements in a specification, are valid forms of separation of concerns that do not necessarily require a modular design.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Dijkstra in his 1974 paper *"On the Role of Scientific Thought"*, coined the term *separation of concerns* in relation to software qualities such as *correctness* and *efficiency*.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Carlo Ghezzi in his book "Fundamentals of software engineering" promotes Separation Of Concerns as the primary way to tackle the inherited complexity in software production.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Philippe Kruchten in his article "Architectural Blueprints—The “4+1” View Model of Software Architecture" used a model composed of five main views to address large architectures, essentially this is a view-based separation of concerns, where each view focus on a different aspect of the architecture.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Laplante, Phillip also mentioned that separation of concerns can be applied in software design, coding, time, and software qualities.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] The term *separation of concerns* was probably coined by Edsger W.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Dijkstra in his 1974 paper "On the role of scientific thought".
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Fifteen years later, it was evident the term *separation of concerns* was becoming an accepted idea.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] SoC is crucial to the design of the Internet.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] In the Internet protocol suite, great efforts have been made to separate concerns into well-defined layers.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] This allows protocol designers to focus on the concerns in one layer, and ignore the other layers.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] The Application Layer protocol SMTP, for example, is concerned about all the details of conducting an email session over a reliable transport service (usually TCP), but not in the least concerned about how the transport service makes that service reliable.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Similarly, TCP is not concerned about the routing of data packets, which is handled at the Internet layer.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] HTML, CSS, and JavaScript are complementary languages used in the development of web pages and websites.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] HTML is mainly used for organization of webpage content, CSS is used for definition of content presentation style, and JavaScript defines how the content interacts and behaves with the user.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Historically, this was not the case: prior to the introduction of CSS, HTML performed both duties of defining semantics and style.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Subject-oriented programming allows separate concerns to be addressed as separate software constructs, each on an equal footing with the others.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Each concern provides its own class-structure into which the objects in common are organized, and contributes state and methods to the composite result where they cut across one another.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Correspondence rules describe how the classes and methods in the various concerns are related to each other at points where they interact, allowing composite behavior for a method to be derived from several concerns.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Multi-dimensional SoC allows the analysis and composition of concerns to be manipulated as a multi-dimensional "matrix" in which each concern provides a dimension in which different points of choice are enumerated, with the cells of the matrix occupied by the appropriate software artifacts.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Aspect-oriented programming allows cross-cutting concerns to be addressed as primary concerns.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] For example, most programs require some form of security and logging.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Security and logging are often secondary concerns, whereas the primary concern is often on accomplishing business goals.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] However, when designing a program, its security must be built into the design from the beginning instead of being treated as a secondary concern.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] Applying security afterwards often results in an insufficient security model that leaves too many gaps for future attacks.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] This may be solved with aspect-oriented programming.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] For example, an aspect may be written to enforce that calls to a certain API are always logged, or that errors are always logged when an exception is thrown, regardless of whether the program's procedural code handles the exception or propagates it.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] In cognitive science and artificial intelligence, it is common to refer to David Marr's levels of analysis.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] At any given time, a researcher may be focusing on what some aspect of intelligence needs to compute, what algorithm it employs, or how that algorithm is implemented in hardware.
[src:code-quality/separation-of-concerns] This separation of concerns is similar to the interface/implementation distinction in software and hardware engineering.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] Technical debt is similar to yet differs significantly from monetary debt.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] Incurring either generally makes future goals more challenging to attain.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] But unlike monetary debt, technical debt is often incurred without intention.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] The choice to minimize development time and cost, an ever-present aspect of business, is the primary factor.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] Technical debt is generally only assessed retroactively (after a development effort).
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] Properly managing technical debt is essential for maintaining software quality and long-term sustainability.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] In some cases, taking on technical debt is a strategic choice to meet immediate goals, such as delivering a proof of concept or a quick release.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] However, failure to prioritize and address the debt can result in reduced maintainability, increased development costs, and risk to production systems.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] Technical debt results from design and implementation decisions that may optimize for the short term, but at the expense of future adaptability and maintainability.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] System aspects that incur technical debt can be described as a collection of design or implementation constructs that make future changes more costly or impossible, primarily impacting internal system qualities such as maintainability and evolvability.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] Ward Cunningham coined the term *technical debt* in 1992.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] Similar concepts had existed before this.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] In 1980, Meir "Manny" Lehman had published a similar law using an "architectural metaphor" for the deteriorating nature of software.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] By increasing the cost of ongoing maintenance, technical debt makes it harder to predict release schedules.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] "Interest payments" result from incomplete work and escalating integration costs due to changes in the upstream project.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] Increases in complexity and the amount of uncompleted work make it increasingly difficult to accurately estimate effort, resulting in delays, missed deadlines, and stress on engineering teams, which can result in higher staff turnover, compounding the problem.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] Carrying technical debt into production increases the risk of outages, financial losses, and potential legal issues due to breached service-level agreements.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] Future refactoring becomes riskier and costlier, with modifications to production code introducing greater chances of disruption.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] Failure to address technical debt can cause productivity to decline and slow down the delivery of features.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] The cumulative effects of technical debt result in increasingly fragile systems that can make bold improvements difficult.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] The domination of incremental changes, along with delays to critical refactoring, can result in stressed systems with inconsistent design, causing users to suffer from degraded performance and limited functionality while developers struggle to maintain quality.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] The development team was unaware it existed until it was exposed during the normal course of performing work on the product.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] For example, the team is adding a new feature to the product and in doing so it realizes that a work-around had been built into the code years before by someone who has long since departed.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] Known to the development team and has been made visible using one of many approaches.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] Known and has been targeted for servicing by the development team.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] The concept of technical debt presumes that an overly-expedient development effort results in additional future costs and that the costs would be avoided if different decisions were made during the effort.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] While true, other considerations impact the potential cost of expedient development decisions.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] For example, if the system does not survive long enough to be modified for a subsequent release, then the savings due to the expedient development choices are true savings since there is no future development cost.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] Future events may render expedient "long-term" designs obsolete.
[src:code-quality/technical-debt] New tools and techniques might reduce the cost of future rework, challenging current debt assumptions.
[src:code-quality/you-aren-t-gonna-need-it] "**You aren't gonna need it**" (**YAGNI**) is a principle which arose from extreme programming (XP) that states a programmer should not add functionality until deemed necessary.
[src:code-quality/you-aren-t-gonna-need-it] Other forms of the phrase include "You aren't going to need it" and "You ain't gonna need it".
[src:code-quality/you-aren-t-gonna-need-it] YAGNI is a principle behind the XP practice of "do the simplest thing that could possibly work" (DTSTTCPW).
[src:code-quality/you-aren-t-gonna-need-it] It is meant to be used in combination with several other practices, such as continuous refactoring, continuous automated unit testing, and continuous integration.
[src:code-quality/you-aren-t-gonna-need-it] Used without continuous refactoring, it could lead to disorganized code and massive rework, known as technical debt.
[src:code-quality/you-aren-t-gonna-need-it] YAGNI's dependency on supporting practices is part of the original definition of XP.
